                     <interp inst="t18311201-260-person1976" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the prisoner's sister. These are my shoes, and I know the money was in the trunk.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-260-person1977">
                  JAMES 
                  BUCKLE
               <interp inst="t18311201-260-person1977" type="surname" value="BUCKLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-260-person1977" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-260-person1977" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             I am an officer. The witnesses sent for me, and gave the prisoner into custody; he had a new jacket on, which he said he bought in Golden-lane, and he said that he had bought a pair of trousers which he gave to another boy, and the rest of the money he had spent in a coffee shop - he said he might as well take his sisters money as any body's; he has been dreadfully neglected: the two young woman bear good characters, and one of them left her place, at Mr. Baker's, to attend to the prisoner.</p>
